article.headline: Philadelphia misses only four shots in fourth quarter
article.linkText: Hot-shooting Sixers on target against Pacers
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Similar to its mid-season turnaround, Philadelphia's resurgence in the fourth quarter was sudden and decisive.
 
Iverson
Allen Iverson had 22 points and 10 assists and the Philadelphia 76ers missed only four shots in the fourth quarter in defeating the Indiana Pacers 91-85 Wednesday night. "It's big, especially considering how close we are," said Keith Van Horn. "We knew how big this was going in and I thought we responded, especially in the second half." Philadelphia (42-28) remained a half-game behind New Jersey in the Atlantic Division, improving to 17-4 since the All-Star break and evening the season series at two wins apiece. The Sixers believe an Eastern Conference championship is within reach. "Nothing's secure. You can slip," Eric Snow said. "We've got goals. We want to win the conference." Indiana, meanwhile, continued to struggle. The Pacers lost for the 15th time in 19 games. Even their home court doesn't help now. After starting the season 21-1 at Conseco Fieldhouse, the Pacers are 7-6 there in their last 13. The Sixers received strong fourth quarters from Iverson, Van Horn and Snow to come back from a five-point deficit at the end of the third. Philadelphia was only 23-for-64 from the floor through the first three quarters before making 11 of its first 13 in the fourth. The Sixers never led until Iverson swished a 19-footer from the left wing to put them ahead 68-67. The Pacers regained a one-point lead after two free throws by Al Harrington with four minutes left, but it would be their last lead of the game. Van Horn, who scored six of his 10 points in the fourth, gave Philadelphia a 78-76 lead on a baseline dunk. Van Horn had injured the hand in the first quarter when he smacked it against the rim, temporarily numbing a few fingers. He reinjured the hand after the dunk and had it wrapped in the locker room. "I thought it might have been broke," he said. Iverson, Van Horn and Derrick Coleman scored successive baskets to cap the 9-0 run and put the Sixers up 84-76. Coleman finished with 13 points and 11 rebounds. Snow added 18 for the Sixers and Kenny Thomas had 10 points and 10 rebounds. After shooting 35 percent in the third quarter -- and getting six points total from Van Horn, Coleman, Iverson and Snow -- the Sixers' offense got on track in the fourth. The Sixers went 13-for-17 in the floor in the fourth and 7-for-8 from the line. "We just kept fighting and understood we had a lot more time to play," Iverson said. "We need to find a way to start playing better in the beginning. Against a lot of teams you can't not play well and expect to turn it on and off." Jermaine O'Neal, playing with a bruised right shoulder, led the Pacers with 24 points and Ron Artest had 15. O'Neal left after colliding with Coleman with about four minutes left in the second quarter. He returned midway through the fourth and scored four straight points to put Indiana ahead 72-70. O'Neal said he hurt his collarbone and didn't think he'd return. O'Neal wasn't sure if he'd play Friday against Chicago. "I don't know if I helped or hurt the team when I came back," he said. The Pacers led by nine early in the third until a quick 9-1 run by the Sixers pulled them within one. The Pacers went back up by six and again Philadelphia came back, again pulling within one. Indiana scored the last five points of the third and led 63-58. "We're still in fourth, but we have a shot at number one," Harrington said. "That's what we've to go focus on." Game notes
The Pacers are considering signing veteran PG Tim Hardaway, who has not played this season. "What he really is insurance," said team president Donnie Walsh. ... Pacers PG Jamaal Tinsley did not play. He was with his family following the passing of his mother on Monday. ... Former Pacers coach Slick Leonard, 70, returned to the broadcast booth for the first time since Jan. 27 following hip replacement surgery. Leonard won a franchise-best 529 games and three ABA championships. ... Colts quarterback Peyton Manning was at the game. ...Reggie Miller scored eight points on three shots in the first half. Iverson needed 16 shots to score nine. ... Brad Miller earned a technical foul in the third.
